- VSCode Version: 1.4
- OS Version: Windows 10

I can't currently support format-on-type in Code because my formatting API can only do full documents. As a next-best-thing I wanted to add format-on-save. However, I'm struggling to find how I can get back to an `editor` in the `onDidSaveTextDocument` event in order to apply this (without looping through open editors, which doesn't seem very clean).

Even if I do go ahead and loop through active editors and find the correct one for my document, applying the editors doesn't seem easy - `executeCommand("vscode.executeFormatDocumentProvider")` returns an array of `TextEdit` but `editor.edit` provides an `editBuilder` that has `insert`/`delete`/`replaced` methods that don't take `TextEdits`. Although I could map them, it seems like I'm probably duplicated a lot of logic that already exists.

The ideal would be a format-on-save option within Code, or the ability to just call format on a document (and have it invoke the provider, apply the edits, return promise)!

``` typescript
onDidSaveTextDocument(document: vs.TextDocument) {
    if (!util.isAnalyzable(document) || document.languageId != "dart")
        return;

    vs.commands.executeCommand("vscode.executeFormatDocumentProvider", document.uri)
        .then((resp: vs.TextEdit[]) => {
            // TODO: Get editor for this document
            // TODO: Convert TextEdits to something that can be passed to EditBuilder?
            // TODO: Then call document.save();
        });
}
```
